        <h3 class="article__heading">Process</h3>

        <h2>Generative research with stakeholders and users</h2>
          <p>Being that they didn‚Äôt have a particular user pain point to address, we proposed starting out with an initial round of stakeholder and user interviews to see if we can find commonalities. The HBR team we‚Äôd be working with this time was much smaller and more focused than the
            <%= link_to(
              "original group of 16.",
              "/case-studies/hbr-curation",
              :class => "anchor-reset",
              :target => "_blank"
              ) %>
          Therefore, we wanted to make sure we heard from stakeholders from other departments (eg. Publishing, Product), to get their perspective and share it with the core team. We wanted to make them feel part of the team and that their insights are being taken into consideration. I figured this would alleviate any pushback that might happen in the end from people who didn‚Äôt feel part of the process.</p>

          <p>Once we heard from stakeholders, we interviewed eight HBR subscribers about their experience with the product to uncover any frustrations or opportunities for improvement. After synthesis, we uncovered five common insights we heard from our subscribers:</p>

          <div class="card card--columns card--list card--blue card-pattern--kiwi">
            <h4 class="card__heading"><span>Subscriber insights</span></h4>
            <div class="card__col">
              <ul class="list list--checks">
                <li>They seek a 1:1 interactive relationship</li>
                <li>They foster connections with others in their field</li>
                <li>They use HBR as a learning/teaching tool for others</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="card__col">
              <ul class="list list--checks">
                <li>HBR fills in training gaps and facilitates leveling up quickly</li>
                <li>They seek more relevant content to them</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>Once we had these insights, I facilitated a Product Design Sprint with the HBR team and two other thoughtbot designers. Usually when you start a Sprint, you have a problem established that you want to solve. Since HBR came to us with the challenge of uncovering a problem, I used the insights as our first step towards identifying a problem. We presented our research, and had the HBR team vote on which insight they would like to move forward with. They used a combination of their expertise and intuition to pick a direction.</p>

          <p>They ultimately converged on: <strong>They use HBR as a learning/teaching tool for others.</strong> It was something they knew about their subscribers, and also knew that they could do more to make this experience better. The most common pain point we heard among subscribers was that they wanted a way to share (gated) content with non-subscribers (their coworkers).</p>

          <h2 class="article__subheader">Product Design Sprint</h2>
          <p>Once we narrowed in on the pain point around sharing content, we went through the Sprint phases to mitigate the risk inherent to bringing a new product to market. We captured the riskiest assumptions that we wanted to validate or invalidate, to ultimately give us the confidence we needed to determine how best we should move forward. We ran through the Understand, Diverge, and Converge phases to establish context, diverge on different ideas, and converge on a solution that we ultimately prototyped and user tested with subscribers the following week.</p>

