        <p>Overall, the subscribers were receptive to this idea of Team Share, and there was more exploration to be done in terms of the execution. We were unsure at this point which was more valuable: sharing with non-subscribers or discussing the article with their team. There was also work to be done around how this factors into HBR‚Äôs existing subscription plans. Would Team Share be available to all subscribers, or would this be an add-on? </p>

        <p>And the most important thing to learn more about is the team member‚Äôs experience, aka, the person who received this shared content. Our interviews focused around the subscriber‚Äôs experience, usually a manger, who would comment on and share an article with their team members. But how would the team member feel about receiving a Team Share? Would contributing to discussions be viewed as extra work? What is a realistic turnaround time for substantive engagement? Is it exciting to gain access to HBR content as a non-subscriber? Would they respond differently if a colleague shared it as opposed to a manager?</p>

        <p>As you can see, this was a juicy problem to sink our teeth into, and I‚Äôm so glad the HBR team wanted to explore it. And! As you probably noticed from the prototype, we tested it as a desktop experience, so ultimately we didn‚Äôt present it as a mobile app, which was the original intention of the sprint. The nature of holding team discussions was best represented in the desktop experience, and we assumed that ideas for a mobile experience would fall out of opportunities that presented themselves in the prototype. It goes to show how important it is to be flexible and open to change. By not allowing ourselves to be boxed into a solution for a mobile app, we were able to address a common pain point we heard across subscribers, that ultimately led to a lot of rich discussion and new ideas and inspiration within the HBR team.</p>
