      <div class="takeaways">
        <h3 class="takeaways__heading featured-content-heading"><span>Takeaways for you and your team</span></h3>
        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>‚ôæÔ∏è Keep testing and iterating</h4>
          <p>We find that doing additional rounds of user testing and prototype iteration after a Sprint are key to getting as many assumptions validated as we can within a short amount of time. This ultimately saves the client so much time and money by helping them narrow their focus quickly to land on an MVP that they are confident in.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>‚ú® Fidelity as a tool</h4>
          <p>As you can see, we used a high-fidelity prototype here. Usually it‚Äôs recommended to keep initial explorations minimal, so as to not mislead the user or distract them with visual design so early on.</p>
          <p>However, because HBR is such a well-known and powerful brand, we feared that we wouldn‚Äôt be taken as seriously without the HBR branding.</p>
          <p>So, we struck a balance between communicating our concepts in a high-level wireframe (lots of buttons that didn‚Äôt work, pages that were suggestive and open-ended), and adding polish through branding and some light visual design treatment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>üîé Synthesis is crucial</h4>
          <p>Synthesizing and communicating your insights from user research is just as‚Äìif not more‚Äìimportant as conducting the research itself. It‚Äôs so important to articulate the insights you‚Äôve landed on and how you came to those conclusions. This way, your team has the opportunity to get on the same page, ask questions, and understand how you make product decisions.</p><p>Think of research as a tool to gain consensus on your team. Overtime, I‚Äôve learned that the most important skill a designer can have is the ability to effectively communicate their informed design decisions.</p>
